<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-055-692  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 055 692.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 15 1990 v24 n3 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>British Telecom takes 'open' advice. ( information systemsmanagement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cortese, Amy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Telecom's Computing and Information Service is respondingto a rapidly changing business and technological environment bylinking its diverse equipment under open systems and standards.andO;The service has chosen Open Systems Interconnect (OSI) as abackbone network and is phasing out IBM's Systems NetworkArchitecture (SNA).andP;  AT and T's Unix System V has been chosen asthe operating system for the service's midrange computers.andP;  IBM'sStructured Query Language (SQL) is required for data management onall hardware.andP;  British Telecom has also inaugurated a majorcomputer-aided software engineering (CASE) effort in order to cutcosts, improve application quality and control applicationcomplexity.andP;  The CASE effort centers on West Germany-based SoftlabInc's Maestro II program, which is centered around object-orientedtechnology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (information services).andO;Product:   Maestro II (Program development software) (business use).andO;Topic:     MISTelephone companiesOpen SystemsStandardsComputer-aided software engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>